    "text": "url: https://hbr.org/2021/07/your-company-needs-a-digital-nomad-policy\ntitle: Your Company Needs a Digital Nomad Policy\ndomain: hbr.org\ncategory: newwork\ndate_scanned: 2026-03-01T09:52:16.492768\nword_count: 196\npaywall: False\n---\n\n# Your Company Needs a Digital Nomad Policy\n\n\n\n\n\n\n---\n\nHarvard Business Review Logo\n\nBusiness management\n\nYour Company Needs a Digital Nomad Policy\n\nby\n\nMiles Everson\n\n,\n\nSteve King\n\nand\n\nCarolyn Ockels\n\nJuly 12, 2021\n\nCavan Images/Getty Images\n\nPost\n\nPost\n\nShare\n\nSave\n\nBuy Copies\n\nPrint\n\nSummary\n\n.\n\nLeer en espa帽ol\n\nLer em portugu锚s\n\nPost\n\nPost\n\nShare\n\nSave\n\nBuy Copies\n\nPrint\n\nIn the months since the Covid-19 pandemic hit, the dramatic and rapid shift to remote work has been perhaps the most potent trend impacting the way businesses operate. It鈥檚 been a particular boon to one growing group of workers: digital nomads. These are people who embrace a location-independent, technology-enabled lifestyle that allows them to travel and work anywhere in the internet-connected world.\n\nMiles Everson\n\nis chief executive officer at MBO Partners, a platform that helps enterprises and self-employed professionals work together easily and compliantly.\n\nSteve King\n\nis a partner at Emergent Research, a research and consulting firm focused on the future of work.\n\nCarolyn Ockels\n\nis the managing partner at Emergent Research, a research and consulting firm focused on the future of work.\n\nPost\n\nPost\n\nShare\n\nSave\n\nBuy Copies\n\nPrint\n\nRead more on\n\nBusiness management\n\nor related topics\n\nOperations and supply chain management\n\nand\n\nRisk management"
